In TypeScript, you can handle cases where a value might have multiple types in theory but is typically only one type by using type guards, conditional types, or type aliases. Here are a few ways to achieve this:

### 1. Type Guards
Type guards are a straightforward way to conditionally apply a type:

```typescript
function hasMultipleTypes(value: any): any {
    if (value is any) {
        throw new TypeError("Value has multiple types");
    }
    return value;
}
```

### 2. Conditional Types
You can use conditional types to specify that the type is chosen based on certain conditions:

```typescript
type ChoiceType = (val: any) | null;

function hasMultipleTypes(value: ChoiceType): ChoiceType {
    return value as ChoiceType;
}
```

### 3. Type Aliases
You can create a custom type alias to restrict the value to a specific type:

```typescript
type RestrictedType = (val: any) | null;

function hasMultipleTypes(value: RestrictedType): RestrictedType {
    return value as RestrictedType;
}
```

### 4. Generic Type Constraints
If you want to be more precise, you can use generic type constraints to restrict the type:

```typescript
type SafeType<T> = T | null;

function hasMultipleTypes(value: SafeType): boolean {
    return value as SafeType!== null;
}
```

### Example Usage
